o COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989 |title=Coronavirus: Premier League and EFL suspended until 3 April at earliest |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Elections including the [[2020 United Kingdom local elections|English local elections]], [[2020 London mayoral election|London mayoral election]] and [[2020 England and Wales police and crime commissioner elections|police and crime commissioner elections]], scheduled for May 2020, are postponed for a year because of the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51876269 |title=Coronavirus: English local elections postponed for a year |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n*14 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: A further 10 people are reported to have died from COVID-19, almost doubling the UK death toll from 11 to 21. The government's aim for a \"[[herd immunity]]\" approach generates controversy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/health/uk-herd-immunity-coronavirus-who-margaret-harris-a4387346.html |title=UK's 'herd immunity' approach to tackling coronavirus questioned by World Health Organisation |work=Evening Standard|date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-51892402 |title=Coronavirus: Scientists say UK virus strategy is 'risking lives' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC News |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://maths.qmul.ac.uk/~vnicosia/UK_scientists_statement_on_coronavirus_measures.pdf |title=Public request to take stronger measures of socialdistancing across the UK with immediate effect |work=Queen Mary University of London |publisher=Queen Mary University of London |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Vice President of the United States]], [[Mike Pence]], announces the US is to extend its European [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States#Travel and entry restrictions|coronavirus travel ban]] to include the UK from 16 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-51891662 |title=Coronavirus: US to extend travel ban to UK and Ireland |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: UK retailers release a joint letter asking customers not to panic buy products after some supermarkets sell out of items such as pasta, hand gel and toilet paper.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51883440 |title=Coronavirus: Supermarkets ask shoppers to be 'considerate' and stop panic buying |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n*15 March \n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] advises against \"all but essential travel\" to the US.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/15/coronavirus-latest-updates-trump-tests-negative-as-spain-orders-nationwide-lockdown-uk-us-australia-italy-europe-global-economy?page=with:block-5e6e17e48f088d7575593aed#block-5e6e17e48f088d7575593aed |title=UK advises against 'all but essential' travel to US |work=The Guardian|date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Health Secretary [[Matt Hancock]] says that every UK resident over the age of 70 will be told \"within the coming weeks\" to self-isolate for \"a very long time\" to shield them from coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51895873 |title=Coronavirus: Isolation for over-70s 'within weeks' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The government announces plans to hold daily televised press conferences to update the public on the fight against the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus pandemic]], starting on Monday 16 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51901818 |title=Coronavirus: Downing Street to give daily update on fight against outbreak |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n*16 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]:  The UK death toll from the coronavirus pandemic reaches 55, with the number of cases of the illness passing 1,500.<ref name=avoid>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51917562 |title=Coronavirus: PM says everyone should avoid office, pubs and travelling |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Prime Minister Boris Johnson advises everyone in the UK against \"non-essential\" travel and contact with others to curb coronavirus, as well as suggesting people should avoid pubs, clubs and theatres, and work from home if possible. Pregnant women, people over the age of 70 and those with certain health conditions are urged to consider the advice \"particularly important\", and will be asked to self-isolate within days.<ref name=avoid/>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The BBC delays its planned changes to TV licences for the over-75s from June to August because of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51911065 |title=Coronavirus: BBC delays over-75 TV licence fee changes |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 March 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n*17 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: NHS England announces that all non-urgent operations in England will be postponed from 15 April to free up 30,000 beds to help tackle the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933410 |title=Coronavirus: All non-urgent operations in England postponed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Hashem Abedi, brother of [[Manchester Arena bombing|Manchester Arena bomber]] [[Salman Abedi]], is found guilty of murdering 22 people in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-51926162 |title=Manchester Arena bombing: Hashem Abedi guilty of 22 murders |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The Chancellor, Rishi Sunak, announces that \u00a3330bn will be made available in loan guarantees for businesses affected by the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/17/boris-johnson-coronavirus-press-conference-rishi-sunak-cabinet-as-rishi-sunak-set-to-announcing-coronavirus-financial-rescue-package-politics-live?page=with:block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b#block-5e71052d8f088d757559527b |title=Sunak says he will make \u00a3330bn available in lending to keep firms in business |work=The Guardian|date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51935467 |title=Coronavirus: Chancellor unveils \u00a3330bn lifeline for economy |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The UK coronavirus-related death toll rises to 71, while the number of confirmed cases of the illness rises to 1,950.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jane |last=Dalton |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/uk-coronavirus-death-toll-nhs-latest-outbreak-pandemic-a9407311.html |title=UK coronavirus death toll rises to 71 |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/uk-coronavirus-cases-reach-1-950-up-407-in-24-hours-11958875 |title=Coronavirus: 14 more deaths in England \u2013 UK total now 71 |publisher=Sky UK |work=Sky News |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n*18 March\n**[[Pound sterling]] falls below $1.18, its lowest level since [[1985 in the United Kingdom|1985]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/40272e84-68ff-11ea-a3c9-1fe6fedcca75 |title=Pound sinks under $1.19 in deepening coronavirus market crisis |publisher=FT |work=FT |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyfx.com/gbp-usd |title=GBP/USD: Pound \u2013 Dollar Rate, Chart, Forecast &amp; Analysis |publisher=Daily FX |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> Bank of England governor [[Andrew Bailey (banker)|Andrew Bailey]], commenting on the UK and wider economic situation, says: \"It's obviously an emergency. I think we're living in completely unparalleled times... It's going to be a very big downturn \u2013 we know that.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-boe-could-take-radical-money-printing-action-11959670 |title=Coronavirus: 'Radical' money printing plan being considered by the Bank of England |work=Sky News |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The UK death toll from coronavirus exceeds 100, with 32 new cases taking the total to 104.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-32-more-covid-19-patients-die-in-england-taking-uk-total-to-104-11959809 |title=Coronavirus: 32 more COVID-19 patients die in England \u2013 taking UK total to 104 |work=Sky News |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The government announces that all schools in the country will shut from the afternoon of Friday 20 March, except for those looking after the children of keyworkers and vulnerable children.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314 |title=Coronavirus: Schools to close until further notice from Friday |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> No exams will take place this academic year, [[Secretary of State for Education|Education Secretary]] [[Gavin Williamson]] confirms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-uk-schools-to-close-from-friday-11959769 |title=Coronavirus: UK schools to close from Friday until further notice |work=Sky News |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The 50th anniversary [[Glastonbury Festival]] is cancelled as a result of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/18/uk-coronavirus-live-boris-johnson-pmqs-cbi-urges-government-pay-businesses-directly-saying-350bn-loangrant-package-not-enough |title=All schools to close from Friday; GCSE and A-level exams cancelled \u2013 UK coronavirus, as it happened |work=The Guardian |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The government announces emergency legislation to bring in a complete ban on new evictions for three months as part of measures to help protect renters in social and private rented accommodation.\n*19 March \u2013 In an emergency move, the Bank of England cuts interest rates again, from 0.25% to just 0.1%. This is the lowest ever in the Bank's 325-year history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51962982 |title=Coronavirus: UK interest rates slashed to lowest level ever |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*20 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Northwick Park Hospital]] in [[London Borough of Harrow|Harrow]] declares a \"critical incident\" due to a surge in patients with coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/news/hospitals-critical-care-unit-overwhelmed-by-coronavirus-patients/7027189.article |title=Hospital's critical care unit overwhelmed by coronavirus patients |work=HSJ |publisher=HSJ|date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Chancellor Rishi Sunak announces that the government will pay 80% of wages for employees not working, up to \u00a32,500 a month, as part of \"unprecedented\" measures to protect people's jobs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51982005 |title=Wages cover for businesses hit by virus outlined |publisher=BBC News|date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Prime Minister Boris Johnson orders all cafes, pubs and restaurants to close from the evening of 20 March, except for take-away food, to tackle coronavirus. All the UK's nightclubs, theatres, cinemas, gyms and leisure centres are told to close \"as soon as they reasonably can\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51981653 |title=UK pubs and restaurants told to shut in virus fight |publisher=BBC News|date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n*21 March \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]] [[George Eustice]] urges shoppers to stop [[panic buying]], as supermarkets around the UK struggle to keep up with demand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51989721 |title=Coronavirus: Shoppers told to buy responsibly |publisher=BBC News|date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> [[Tesco]], [[Asda]], [[Aldi]], and [[Lidl]] are reported to have begun a recruitment drive for up to 30,000 new staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51976075 |title=Supermarkets Tesco, Asda, Aldi and Lidl go on hiring spree |publisher=BBC News|date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n*22 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The [[Nursing and Midwifery Council]] announces that more than 5,600 former nurses have registered to offer their services in the fight against coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/22/uk-coronavirus-live-police-could-enforce-london-lockdown-says-khan-seven-people-die-in-wales?page=with:block-5e776a4f8f08dcc95cc20fdd#block-5e776a4f8f08dcc95cc20fdd |title=UK coronavirus live: police could enforce London social distancing; seven people die in Wales |work=The Guardian|date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Boris Johnson warns that \"tougher measures\" may be introduced if people do not follow government advice on social distancing.<ref name=\"tougher measures\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51998559 |title=Coronavirus: Follow virus advice or 'tougher measures' likely, says PM |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> \n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The virus claims its youngest victim so far with the death of an eighteen-year-old with underlying health problems.<ref name=\"tougher measures\"/>\n*23 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The government announces emergency measures to safeguard the nation's [[Rail transport in the United Kingdom|rail network]], with season ticket holders given refunds if working from home, and rail franchise agreements nationalised for at least six months to prevent rail companies from collapsing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52002272 |title=Commuters to get refund on rail season tickets |publisher=BBC News|date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-rail-franchise-agreements-suspended-to-avoid-company-collapses-11962186 |title=Coronavirus: Rail franchise agreements suspended to avoid company collapses |publisher=Sky News|date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Pride in London]], the UK's largest LGBT [[Pride festival]], scheduled for 27 June, is the latest event to be postponed. It is one of a hundred pride events to be postponed or cancelled in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hunte |first=Ben |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52001388 |title=Coronavirus postpones London Pride |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Alex Salmond]] is cleared of sexually assaulting nine women while he was [[First Minister of Scotland|Scotland's First Minister]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-52004285 |title=Alex Salmond cleared of all sexual assault charges| publisher=BBC | date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: In a televised address, Boris Johnson announces a UK-wide lockdown with immediate effect, to contain the spread of the coronavirus. People can leave their homes only for \"very limited purposes\" \u2013 shopping for basic necessities; for one form of exercise a day; for any medical need; and to travel to and from work when \"absolutely necessary\". A number of other restrictions are imposed, with police given powers to enforce the measures, including the use of fines.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-52000039 |title='You must stay at home' UK public told| publisher=BBC | date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52012432 |title=Coronavirus: Strict new curbs on life in UK announced by PM| publisher=BBC | date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/23/boris-johnson-orders-uk-lockdown-to-be-enforced-by-police |title=Boris Johnson orders UK lockdown to be enforced by police| work=The Guardian| date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n*24 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The UK records its highest number of coronavirus deaths in one day, after another 87 people die across the country, bringing the total to 422.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-calls-for-police-at-stations-after-packed-trains-defy-lockdown-11962837|title=Coronavirus: Biggest daily rise in UK deaths \u2013 up by 87 to 422\n| publisher=Sky News| date=24 March 2020| accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: For the first time, all of the UK's [[List of mobile network operators of Europe#United Kingdom|mobile networks]] send out a government text alert, ordering people to stay at home. The message reads: \"''GOV.UK CORONAVIRUS ALERT. New rules in force now: you must stay at home. More info and exemptions at gov.uk/coronavirus Stay at home. Protect the NHS. Save lives.''\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52017451|title=Coronavirus: Mobile networks send 'stay at home' text| publisher=BBC News| date=24 March 2020| accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Secretary of State for Health|Health secretary]] [[Matt Hancock]] announces the government will open a temporary hospital, the [[NHS Nightingale Hospital London]] at the [[Excel London]], to add extra critical care capacity in response to coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52018477|title=Coronavirus: ExCeL Centre planned as NHS field hospital| publisher=BBC News| date=24 March 2020| accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n*25 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Prince Charles]] tests positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52033845|title=Coronavirus: Prince Charles tests positive but 'remains in good health'| publisher=BBC News| date=25 March 2020| accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] shuts down for a month.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52032188|title=Coronavirus: Parliament shuts down for a month| publisher=BBC News| date=25 March 2020| accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[British Transport Police]] deploys 500 officers to patrol the UK's rail network, in an effort to discourage non-essential journeys. New measures are also introduced on the [[London Underground]] to reduce passenger numbers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52023580|title=Coronavirus: New Tube restrictions to stop non-essential journeys| publisher=BBC News| date=25 March 2020| accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n*26 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The government announces that the [[Self-employment|self-employed]] will be paid 80% of profits, up to \u00a32,500 a month, to help them cope during the economic crisis triggered by COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52053914|title=Coronavirus: UK government unveils aid for self-employed| publisher=BBC News| date=26 March 2020| accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: At 8pm, millions of people around the country take part in a \"Clap for Carers\" tribute, applauding the NHS and other care workers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52058013|title=Clap for Carers: UK in 'emotional' tribute to NHS and care workers| publisher=BBC News| date=27 March 2020| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*27 March\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Prime Minister Boris Johnson tests positive for COVID-19, and will self-isolate in [[10 Downing Street]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52060791|title=PM Boris Johnson tests positive for coronavirus| publisher=BBC News| date=27 March 2020| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Health Secretary [[Matt Hancock]] tests positive for COVID-19 and reports that he is working from home and self-isolating.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-matt-hancock-boris-johnson-test-positive-covid-19-symptoms-a9430031.html|title=Coronavirus: Health secretary Matt Hancock tests positive| work=The Independent| date=27 March 2020| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*31 March \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: A significant rise in [[anxiety]] and [[Depression (mood)|depression]] among the UK population is reported following the lockdown. The study, by researchers from the [[University of Sheffield]] and [[Ulster University]], finds that people reporting anxiety increased from 17% to 36%, while those reporting depression increased from 16% to 38%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/rise-in-depression-and-anxiety-day-after-uk-lockdown-announced-study-coronavirus |title=Rise in depression and anxiety day after UK lockdown announced \u2013 study| work=The Guardian| date=31 March 2020| accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n*1 April\n**The [[contactless payment]] limit for in-store spending is raised from \u00a330 to \u00a345.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2020/mar/24/limit-for-contactless-spending-to-rise-to-45-at-beginning-of-april|title=Limit for contactless spending to rise to \u00a345 at beginning of April|work=The Guardian|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The UK's [[National Living Wage]] rises from \u00a38.21 to \u00a38.72, an increase of 6.2%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/inews-lifestyle/money/minimum-wage-increase-2020-april-rise-new-national-living-uk-pay-when-change-date-1352523|title=Minimum wage increase April 2020: what the new UK national living wage is and who gets a pay rise today|publisher=I News|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n*3 April \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[NHS Nightingale Hospital London]], the first temporary critical care hospital to treat Covid-19 patients, opens at the [[ExCeL London|ExCel centre]] in East London, employing NHS staff and military personnel, with a bed capacity of up to 4,000. It is the first of several [[NHS COVID-19 critical care hospitals|temporary critical care hospitals]] planned across the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52150598|title=Coronavirus: Nightingale Hospital opens at London's ExCel centre|work=BBC News|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n*4 April \u2013 The results of the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]] and the [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election]] are announced, in which [[Keir Starmer]] is elected as the leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], succeeding [[Jeremy Corbyn]], and [[Angela Rayner]] is elected as deputy leader of the party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52164589|title=Keir Starmer elected as new Labour leader|work=BBC News|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*5 April\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Queen Elizabeth II]] makes a [[Addresses to the nation by Elizabeth II|rare broadcast to the UK]] and the wider Commonwealth, something she has done on only four previous occasions. In the address she thanks people for following the government's social distancing rules and pays tribute to key workers, and says the UK \"will succeed\" in its fight against coronavirus but may have \"more still to endure\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Caroline |last=Davies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/03/queen-to-address-nation-on-sunday-over-coronavirus-crisis |title=Queen to address nation on Sunday over coronavirus crisis |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=3 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52176222 |title=Coronavirus: Queen tells UK 'we will succeed' in fight |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Prime Minister Boris Johnson is admitted to hospital for tests after testing positive for coronavirus ten days earlier.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52177125 |title=Coronavirus: PM admitted to hospital over virus symptoms |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n*6 April\n**[[Debenhams]], one of the UK's largest and oldest department stores, goes into administration for the second time in a year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/apr/06/debenhams-appoint-administrators-second-time-in-year-coronavirus-lockdown|title=Debenhams to appoint administrators for second time in a year|publisher=The Guardian|date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The death toll from COVID-19 in the UK exceeds 5,000. The total number of reported cases is nearly 52,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/apr/06/uk-coronavirus-live-boris-johnson-spends-night-in-hospital?page=with:block-5e8b4c078f080bdb9f535404#block-5e8b4c078f080bdb9f535404|title=UK death toll rises to 5,373|publisher=The Guardian|date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] is taken into [[intensive care unit|intensive care]] after being admitted to hospital for coronavirus the day before. It is announced that [[First Secretary of State]] [[Dominic Raab]] will deputise for him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52192604 |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson moved to intensive care |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n*8 April \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The [[Resolution Foundation]], using figures from the [[British Chambers of Commerce]], reports that more than nine million workers are expected to be [[Furlough|furloughed]] under the government's job retention scheme, with an estimated cost to the taxpayer of between \u00a330 and 40bn.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52209790 |title=Coronavirus: More than 9 million expected to be furloughed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n*9 April\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Foreign Secretary [[Dominic Raab]] says the UK is \"starting to see the impact\" of the restrictions but that it is \"too early\" to lift them, and urges people to stay indoors over the Easter weekend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52235492|title=Raab urges UK public not to ruin lockdown progress|publisher=BBC News|date=9 April 2020}}</ref> \n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] is moved out of intensive care, but remains in hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52238276|title=PM out of intensive care but remains in hospital|publisher=BBC News|date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n*11 April \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Queen Elizabeth II]] makes her first ever [[Easter]] message to the nation, in which she states \"coronavirus will not overcome us\" and that \"we need Easter as much as ever.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52255054 |title=Coronavirus: 'We need Easter as much as ever,' says the Queen |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=11 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n*12 April\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] is discharged from hospital after being treated for coronavirus and will continue his recovery at [[Chequers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52262012 |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson discharged from hospital |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: The number of people who died in hospital with coronavirus in the UK passes 10,000, after a daily rise of 737.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52264145 |title=Coronavirus: 'Sombre day' as UK deaths hit 10,000 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n*16 April\n**A 99-year-old war veteran, [[Tom Moore (fundraiser)|Tom Moore]], raises over \u00a313&nbsp;million (subsequently raised over \u00a325&nbsp;million) for [[NHS Charities Together]] after walking more than 100 laps of his garden, with hundreds of thousands (subsequently over a million) of people donating to his [[JustGiving]] page.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52303859 |title=Coronavirus: Capt Tom Moore finishes NHS fundraiser as it tops \u00a313m |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Foreign Secretary [[Dominic Raab]] announces a three-week extension to the nationwide lockdown measures as the number of confirmed COVID-19 cases in the UK surpasses 100,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52313715 |title=Coronavirus: UK lockdown extended for 'at least three weeks' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n*19 April &ndash; [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Michael Gove]], in a BBC interview with [[Andrew Marr]], concedes that the Prime Minister missed five [[Cabinet_Office_Briefing_Rooms|COBRA]] meetings in the early stages of the viral outbreak, and that the UK shipped [[personal protective equipment|protective equipment]] to China in February.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/19/michael-gove-fails-to-deny-pm-missed-five-coronavirus-cobra-meetings |title=Boris Johnson missed five coronavirus Cobra meetings, Gove says |work=The Guardian |publisher=The Guardian |date=19 April 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n*21 April \u2013 [[COVID-19 in the UK]]: Data from the [[Office for National Statistics (United Kingdom)|Office for National Statistics]] show the number of deaths in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in England|England]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Wales|Wales]] has risen to its highest in 20 years. Figures show 18,500 deaths were recorded in the week up to 10 April, 8,000 more than usual for this time of year, with one in three linked to COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52361519 |title=Coronavirus: Deaths at 20-year high but peak may be over |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=21 April 2020 |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n*22 April \n**MPs take part in the first \"virtual\" [[Prime Minister's Questions]], via video conferencing service [[Zoom_Video_Communications|Zoom]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lbc.co.uk/news/first-virtual-prime-ministers-questions-watch-live/ |title=The first \"Virtual\" Prime Minister's Questions: Watch live NOW |work=LBC |publisher=LBC |date=22 April 2020 |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[COVID-19 in the UK]]: [[Chief Medical Officer for England|Chief Medical Officer]] [[Chris Whitty]] says it is likely the UK will have to live under some disruptive social distancing measures for at least the rest of the year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52389285 |title=Coronavirus: Social restrictions 'to remain for rest of year' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=22 April 2020 |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Predicted and scheduled events ===\n* November \u2013 Glasgow is scheduled to host the 26th Conference of the Parties of the [[UN Framework Convention on Climate Change]] (UNFCCC) \u2013 a major UN climate change summit.<ref>{{cite news|first=Will |last=Hazell |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/2020-calendar-summits-elections-sporting-events-1353215 |title=2020 calendar: The major international summits, elections and sporting events of the year ahead |publisher=inews |date=1 January 2020 |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n* 31 December \u2013 The current expiration to the transition period, and deadline for negotiations on a future UK-EU relationship, after Brexit.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/uk-politics-50838994 |title=Brexit: What is the transition period? |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=20 December 2019 |accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Deaths ==\n\n=== January ===\n[[File:Derek Acorah 2013 2013-11-21 01-05 (cropped).jpeg|upright|thumb|[[Derek Acorah]] in 2013]]\n[[File:Roger Scruton by Pete Helme.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Roger Scruton|Sir Roger Scruton]]]]\n[[File:Derek Fowlds Allan Warren.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Derek Fowlds]] in 1974]]\n[[File:Official portrait of Lord Maclennan of Rogart crop 2.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Robert Maclennan, Baron Maclennan of Rogart]] in 2018]]\n[[File:Terry Jones Monty Python O2 Arena (cropped).jpg|upright|thumb|[[Terry Jones]] in 2014]]\n[[File:Nicholas Parsons 2007.png|upright|thumb|[[Nicholas Parsons]] in 2007]]\n*1 January\n**[[Chris Barker]], 39, English footballer ([[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]], [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/50971215|title=Chris Barker: Former Cardiff City defender dies aged 39|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|date=2 January 2020|access-date=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Alexander Frater]], 82, travel writer and journalist.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/commentisfree/2020/jan/05/obituary-alexander-frater-1937-2020|last=Chesshyre|first=Robert|title=Obituary: Alexander Frater 1937\u20132020|work=The Guardian|date=5 January 2020|access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n*3 January\n**[[Derek Acorah]], 69, self-styled spiritual medium and television personality (''[[Most Haunted]]'', ''[[Derek Acorah's Ghost Towns]]'').<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-50991908|title=Derek Acorah, TV medium, dies aged 69|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Christopher Beeny]], 78, actor (''[[Upstairs, Downstairs (1971 TV series)|Upstairs, Downstairs]]'', ''[[In Loving Memory (TV series)|In Loving Memory]]'', ''[[Last of the Summer Wine]]'').<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51035015|title=Christopher Beeny: Upstairs, Downstairs actor dies at 78|work=BBC News|date=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n*4 January\n**[[Guy Arnold]], 87, explorer and writer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/guy-arnold-obituary-hpbxnj9jl|title=Guy Arnold obituary|work=The Times|date=24 January 2020|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Jack Baldwin (chemist)|Sir Jack Baldwin]], 81, chemist.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.chemistryviews.org/details/ezine/11210979/Sir_Jack_Edward_Baldwin_1938__2020.html|title=Sir Jack Edward Baldwin (1938\u20132020)|publisher=Chemistry Views|date=10 January 2020|access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n*5 January\n**[[James Barber (biochemist)|James Barber]], 79, biochemist.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rutherford|first=Bill|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/194710/professor-james-barber-1940-2020/|title=Professor James Barber, 1940\u20132020|publisher=Imperial College London|date=13 January 2020|access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Colin Howson]], 74\u201375, philosopher.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lse.ac.uk/philosophy/blog/2020/01/08/colin-howson-1945-2020/|title=Colin Howson, 1945\u20132020|publisher=London School of Economics|date=8 January 2020|access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Sir Michael Stear]], 81, [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] air chief marshal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/deaths/238672/stear|title=Stear|publisher=Daily Telegraph: Announcements|date=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n*6 January\n**[[Ray Byrom]], 85, English footballer ([[Accrington Stanley F.C. (1891)|Accrington Stanley]], [[Bradford (Park Avenue) A.F.C.|Bradford (Park Avenue)]]).<ref>{{cite news|last=Athey|first=Neil|url=https://www.thelancasterandmorecambecitizen.co.uk/news/18151114.ex-accrington-stanley-player-founder-garage-supplies-firm-ray-byrom-dies/|title=Ex-Accrington Stanley player and founder of garage supplies firm Ray Byrom dies|work=The Lancaster and Morecambe Citizen|date=10 January 2020|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Danny Masterton]], 65, Scottish footballer ([[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]], [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2020/01/06/6303/|title=Danny Masterton|publisher=Clyde F.C.|date=6 January 2020|access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[James Mehaffey]], 88, Northern Irish Anglican prelate, [[Bishop of Derry and Raphoe]] (1980\u20132002).<ref>{{cite news|last=McClements|first=Freya|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/former-coi-bishop-of-derry-dr-james-mehaffy-dies-aged-88-1.4132223|title=Former CoI bishop of Derry Dr James Mehaffy dies aged 88|work=Irish Times|date=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n*7 January\n**[[Gerald Bowden]], 84, politician, [[Member of Parliament|MP]] (1983\u20131992).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/obituaries/2020/01/07/gerald-bowden-tory-politician-cut-teeth-ilea-mp-dulwich-welcomed/|title=Gerald Bowden, Tory politician who cut his teeth at Ilea and as MP for Dulwich welcomed Mrs Thatcher to the area \u2013 obituary|work=The Telegraph|date=7 January 2020|access-date=8 January 2020}} {{paywall}}</ref>\n**[[Stephen Clements]], 47, radio personality ([[BBC Radio Ulster]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-51022614|title=Stephen Clements: BBC Radio Ulster presenter dies age 47|publisher=BBC News|date=7 January 2020|access-date=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Colin Seeley]], 84, motorcycle engineer and racer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.motorcyclenews.com/sport/2020/january/colin-seeley-died/|title=Colin Seeley, legendary frame builder, has died aged 84|work=Motorcycle News|date=8 January 2020|access-date=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n*8 January\n**[[Peter T. Kirstein]], 86, German-born computer scientist.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hafner|first=Katie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/08/technology/peter-kirstein-dead.html|title=Peter Kirstein, Father of the European Internet, Is Dead at 86|work=The New York Times|date=8 January 2020|access-date=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[David Montgomery, 2nd Viscount Montgomery of Alamein]], 91, peer and businessman, member of the [[House of Lords]] (1976\u20131999, 2005\u20132015).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/deaths/238707/montgomery|title=Montgomery|publisher=Daily Telegraph: Announcements|date=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n*9 January\n**[[The Alexander Brothers|Tom Alexander]], 85, musician ([[The Alexander Brothers]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-51064069|title=Tom Alexander of The Alexander Brothers dies aged 85|work=BBC News|date=10 January 2020|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[John Brownjohn]], 90, literary translator.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/deaths/238583/brownjohn|title=Brownjohn|publisher=Daily Telegraph: Announcements|date=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Jimmy Shields (footballer)|Jimmy Shields]], 88, Northern Irish footballer ([[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]], [[Oxford United F.C.|Headington United]], [[Northern Ireland national football team|national team]]).<ref>{{cite news|last=Bull|first=David|url=https://www.southamptonfc.com/news/2020-01-10/obituary-jimmy-shields-southampton-football-club|title=Jimmy Shields: An appreciation|publisher=Southampton F.C.|date=10 January 2020|access-date=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n*10 January\n**[[Alun Gwynne Jones, Baron Chalfont]], 100, politician, [[Minister of State for Foreign Affairs (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Foreign Affairs]] (1964\u20131970) and member of the [[House of Lords]] (1964\u20132015).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/lord-chalfont-obituary-r5r3mgz8d|title=Lord Chalfont obituary|work=The Times|date=14 January 2020}} {{paywall}}</ref>\n**[[Roddy Lumsden]], 53, poet.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloodaxebooks.com/news?articleid=1006|title=Roddy Lumsden (1966\u20132020)|publisher=Bloodaxe Books|date=11 January 2020|access-date=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n*12 January\n**[[Jackie Brown (Scottish boxer)|Jackie Brown]], 84, Scottish boxer, [[List of Commonwealth Games medallists in boxing|Commonwealth Games]] gold medallist ([[1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|1958]]), [[List of British flyweight boxing champions|British]] and [[List of Commonwealth Boxing Council champions|Commonwealth]] flyweight champion (1962\u20131963).<ref>{{cite news|last=McKenzie|first=James|url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/people/edinburgh-boxing-champion-jackie-brown-who-once-shared-dressing-room-muhammad-ali-dies-aged-84-after-dementia-battle-1363613|title=Edinburgh boxing champion Jackie Brown who once shared dressing room with Muhammad Ali, dies aged 84 after dementia battle|work=Edinburgh Evening News|date=13 January 2020|access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Tony Garnett]], 83, television and film producer (''[[Kes (film)|Kes]]'', ''[[Eart